Several types of '''Ainu fiddle''' have been described by anthropologists of the [[Ainu people]] of Northern Japan and the adjoining [[Russian Far East]] islands of [[Sakhalin]] and [[Kuril]].
The missionary-anthropologist [[John Batchelor (missionary)|John Batchelor]] noted of the Sakhalin Ainu (1901):
{{quote|''The Ainu of Saghlien make a sort of fiddle, some with two, some with three, and others with four or even more strings, according to caprice. There are several of these to be seen in the Sapporo Museum, and others are found among some of those Ishkari Ainu who originally came down from Saghalien when that island was ceded to Russia.''<ref>{{cite book|last=Batchelor|first=John|title=The Ainu and Their Folk-lore|year=1901|publisher=Religious Tract Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x3AAAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA273#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> }}
And further of those of [[Karafuto]] (1892):
{{quote|''The Karafuto Ainu are said to have a kind of fiddle with two strings, and another with three, but I have never seen these''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Batchelor|first=John|title=The Ainu of Japan: The Religion, Superstitions, and General History of the Hairy Aborigines of Japan|year=1892|publisher=Religious Tract Society|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zadFAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA129#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>}}
