{{Infobox hotel | hotel_name =Hotel Africa | logo = | logo_width= | image = | image_width = | caption = | location =[[Virginia, Liberia|Virginia]], [[Greater Monrovia District]], [[Liberia]] | pushpin_map =Liberia | coordinates = {{coord|6|24|9|N|10|48|39|W|display=inline}} | coordinates_type = | opening_date = | stars = | diamonds = | closing_date = | developer = | architect = | operator = | owner = | number_of_restaurants = | number_of_rooms = | number_of_suites = | floor_area = | floors = | parking = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Hotel Africa''' is a hotel on the western coast of [[Liberia]] in the northern [[Monrovia]] suburb of [[Virginia, Liberia|Virginia]].
In 1979, the hotel, the largest in Liberia, hosted the [[Organisation of African Unity]] conference. The conference was led by President [[William R. Tolbert, Jr.]] who was the group's chair at the time, just months before he was overthrown by [[Samuel Doe]].<ref name="Huband1998">{{cite book|last=Huband|first=Mark|title=The Liberian Civil War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X1BVJZMDYMwC&pg=PA180|accessdate=28 April 2012|date=30 June 1998|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-7146-4785-2|page=180}}</ref> During the Liberian Civil War, many pilots of Russian and Ukrainian origin stayed at the hotel.<ref name="Williams2002">{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Gabriel I. H.|title=Liberia: The Heart of Darkness : Accounts of Liberia's Civil War and Its Destabilizing Effects in West Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r6qZMoquA28C&pg=PA416|accessdate=28 April 2012|year=2002|publisher=Trafford Publishing|isbn=978-1-55369-294-2|page=416}}</ref> In the 1980s the hotel was owned by British-Liberian businessman [[Michael Doe (businessman)|Michael Doe]].<ref name="Sherman2010">{{cite book|last=Sherman|first=Frank|title=Liberia: The Land, Its People, History and Culture|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ElYD-kYiLtMC&pg=PA297|accessdate=28 April 2012|date=31 January 2010|publisher=Godfrey Mwakikagile|isbn=978-9987-16-025-9|page=297}}</ref> On 5 August, 1990, the [[INPFL]] kidnapped the manager Doe, two Lebanese, and two Liberians at the Hotel Africa, later murdering Michael Doe, throwing him off the 4th floor balcony.<ref name="State">{{cite book|author=United States, Bureau of Diplomatic Security, Dept. of State|title=Significant Incidents of Political Violence Against Americans 1990|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uG_w1ie6ligC&pg=PA16|accessdate=28 April 2012|publisher=DIANE Publishing|isbn=978-1-4289-6571-3|page=16}}</ref>
A South African consortium had plans to invest US$100 million to renovate the historic hotel in time for Liberia's hosting duties of an international women's colloquium in 2009.
