'''Orba''', also known as '''X-2''', was intended to be the first [[satellite]] launched by a [[United Kingdom|British]] rocket. It was launched at 00:34 [[GMT]] on 2 September 1970, atop a [[Black Arrow]] rocket from [[Woomera Launch Area 5|Launch Area 5B]] at [[Woomera Test Range|Woomera]], but failed to reach orbit after the second stage of the carrier rocket shut down 13 seconds early.<ref name="EA-BA">{{cite web|url=http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/blaarrow.htm|title=Black Arrow|last=Wade|first=Mark|publisher=[[Encyclopedia Astronautica]]|accessdate=2008-10-28|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071206111804/http://www.astronautix.com/lvs/blaarrow.htm|archivedate=6 December 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Orba was built from spare parts due to funding restrictions,<ref name="VE-BA">{{cite web|url=http://www.spaceuk.org/ba/ba.htm|title=Black Arrow|last=Hill|first=Nicholas|work=A Vertical Empire|publisher=Space UK|accessdate=2008-10-28}}</ref> and was to have been used to measure upper atmosphere density by monitoring the [[orbital decay|decay]] of its orbit.<ref name="GSP">{{cite web|url=http://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/orba.htm|title=Orba (X 2)|last=Krebs|first=Gunter|publisher=Gunter's Space Page|accessdate=2008-10-28}}</ref>
